Here's a Python function that can help you determine if a given number is a prime number:

```python
def is_prime(number):
    if number <= 1:
        return False
    for i in range(2, int(number**0.5) + 1):
        if number % i == 0:
            return False
    return True
```

This function takes a number as an input and checks if it's greater than 1 (since 1 is not considered a prime number). It then iterates through numbers from 2 to the square root of the given number (rounded up to the nearest integer). If the given number is divisible by any of these numbers, it returns `False`, indicating that the number is not prime. If the given number is not divisible by any of these numbers, it returns `True`, indicating that the number is a prime number.

In a LATEX document, you can automatically generate a table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command. This command is typically placed right after the preamble (between the `\documentclass` and `\begin{document}` commands) or at the desired location in the document. Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\usepackage{tocloft} % This package provides customization options for the table of contents

\begin{document}

\renewcommand{\cftsecfont}{\normalfont\bfseries} % Customize section font
\renewcommand{\cftsecpagefont}{\normalfont} % Customize section page font

\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents

\section{Section One}
This is the content of Section One.

\subsection{Subsection One}
This is the content of Subsection One under Section One.

\section{Section Two}
This is the content of Section Two.

\end{document}
```

In this example, we use the `tocloft` package to customize the font for section headings and page numbers in the table of contents. The `\tableofcontents` command automatically generates the table of contents based on the sectioning commands (`\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) used in the document.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX using the FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) provided, you can use the `chessboard` package. FEN represents the entire state of a chess game, including the position of the pieces, the castling rights, and the state of the en passant square.

Here's a LaTeX code snippet that demonstrates how to draw a chessboard using FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}
\begin{chessboard}
\setfen{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\end{chessboard}
\end{document}
```

In this example, the FEN notation is `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1`. You can replace this with your desired FEN string. The `\setfen` command takes the FEN string as an argument and sets up the chessboard accordingly.

Make sure to replace the provided FEN string with the one you want to use. This code will produce an image of the chessboard with the given state.

